ricts that offer Open Choice seats. Efforts to expand Open Choice and to ensure equal access to all Hartford students should begin with investigations of why Hispanic students, males, and students from the southern sections of the city are less likely to participate." Note that although authors claim that "student race is not used in determining admissions" (p. 1), the CT statutes restrict the degree of participation by race and residence (see my Sheff chapter).},
