onsiderable." pxiii Ch1 The second ghetto and the dynamics of neighborhood change contrast between interracial violence of 1919 "communal" riot with white mobs attacking black ghettos vs property damage of 1968 "commodity" riot after King's assassination path was not ineviatable, but determined by degree of governmental intervention, but expansion of second ghetto was sanctioned and supported by govt - siting of public housing projects  - HOLC and FHA indirectly furthered seg by support white mid-class sub flight late 1930s Ida B Wells homes supported by black press, despite segregation, due to dire need for decent housing; with many black trade workers, yet by 1943 black Chicagoans protested National Housing Agency dference to local restrictive covenants push-pull factors of second migration, leading to severe housing shortage amid rise of WWII defense industry diverted away from construction "the coincidence of plentiful jobs and scarce housing" p20 crisis grew worse after WWII; dilapidated construction 1950s suburban exodus reshaped central city "As the more well-to-do whites were selectively drained from Chicago's core, vacancies began to appear around the Black Belt. The desperate need for new housing and the blacks' iimproved economic condition combined to render old borders unstable. The undersidie of the process of suburbanization was the redefinition of the city's geographical racial accommodation" p27 suburban housing boom and falling share of city population increasing black income from 1950 to 1960, but rents in black areas 10-25\% higher than equivalent white areas, greater in racial succession areas p29 "The forces promoting a durable and unchanging racial border -- the dual housing market, the cost of black housing, restrictive covenants -- were, at first, buttressed by the housing shortage. Once new construction began, however, those same forces became an overwhelmingly powerful engine for change. With an increase in housing alternatives for whites, 