s it was the fear that they would be dispossessed that inspired the most antiblack sentiment" p35; cannot compete against middle-class blacks for housing overcrowded, dilapidated outcomes led most whites to infer that black inmigration led to physical deterioration; white reactions ranged from violence/arson to reshaping environment with 'urban planning' p36; Southside Planning Assocation created 1939 to design "ingenious ways of preventing Negroes from moving into the area"; SPA bought property back from blacks moving in p37; SPA involved in passage of IL Redev Act of 1941 to demolish black settlement and move them to all-black suburb (but not accomplished)Ch2 An era of hidden violence in contrast to 1919 riot over labor-racial strife, 1947 riot period over shift in racial territory and housing, which later gave way to 1950s battles over use of community facilities Ch3 Friends, neighbors, and rioters analysis of those arrested in riots, residential proximity to riot area; local struggles over turf; also ethnicity, occ status, etc Ch4 The Loop versus teh slums: downtown strikes back in response to expansion of ghetto and central city deterioration, large downtown institutions "used their combined economic resources and political influence to produce a redevelopment and urban renewal program designed to gurantee their continued prosperity"; paralle reaction to white ethnic working class, but less violent p100 private interests used public policy (redevelopment acts of 1947, 1953) to protect themselves "Although humanistic concern for the quality of life in [Loop] areas was often expressed, simple economics governed the Loop's devotion to its hinterland. Chicago's gbusiness elite clearly envisaged a postware building boom ion the city's periphery, the flight of the middle class, and the insulation of State Street from its 'normal market'. They subsequently tried to counter the forces promoting decentralization thorugh the 'complet rehabiltation of the center of the city'. 'The real purpose of redevelopment, one knowledgeable observer later noted, was 'to reattract solvent population and investment to the dying areas of teh city'." p101 class and racial differences between redeveloped area's old and new tenants Ch5 A neighborhood on a hill: Hyde Park and the Univ of Chicago 1952-53 redevelopment program; "as was the case with the Blighted Areas Redevelopment Act of 1947, the local program pioneered in chicago later served as a model for the federal legislation that spread the concept of 'urban renewal' across the nation" p136 neighborhood 'conservation' program that avoided annexation into growing Black Belt Ch6 Divided we stand: white unity and the color line at midcentury [see Sugrue and Seligman 2003 commentaries on author's early use of 'whiteness' category] "Nothing would have shocked Hyde Parkers more than the assertion that they were part of a generalized 'white' effort to control the process of racial succession in Chicago. The imputation of brotherhood with the ethnic, working-class rock throwers would have been more than they could bear. Yet, there was just such a consensus. Each of the various white groups or interests agreed on the fundamental undesirability of racial succession. Each of them were, for their own reasons, unable or unwilling to flee the city, and each believed that the profcess ahd to be controlled to project their self [171] defed interests. There was certainly wide divergence int eh means deemed acceptable to manage succession, but th Hypde Park proclivity for sending building inspectors rather than debris into the homes of new black residents stemmed from the same fears that called forth crowds elsewhere.... Although the rhetoric of integration was in sharp contrast tothe virulent racist diatribes that were offered in some quarters, the justification given for actions tkane reveal the differences among the various white groups to be more in the vehemence of language and the sophistication of the resistance than in fundamental assumptions." p171-72 acculturation theory and generalizing of all blacks author identifies "merging of the 'ethnics' ". .. "to assert their 'whiteness,' their bade of rank and status in teir adopted home" p186 neighborhood newspapers: "Indeed, the whites around Trumbull Park constucted their own immigrant/black analogy,k which adhered more closely to their own perspective. Nobody was 'poorer' than the European immigrants, the Bulletin claimed, and yet their accomplishments were achieved without governmetn aid; they 'just worked like hell [186 end] and saved for a rainy day'. Let the blacks, it was concluded, do the same." p186-87 opponents to black neighbors were "welded together by an intense race consciousness. The South Deering Bulletin submerged nationality and stated the case plainty: 'White people built this area [and] we want no part of this race mixing..Race pride has come to the fore as a new set of values'." p187 "Significantly, this deep concern for 'white,' not 'ethnic,' rights was often heard in taverns where Polish remained the primary language." p187 Ch7 Making the second ghetto downtown business interests exerted stronger power through redevelopment public policy (for their private interests) than did white ethnic working-class neighborhood groups, which did exert limited pressure (through violent riots) on public orgs like Chicago Housing Authority to segregate neighborhoods; yet both white groups had more power than Chicago blacks, locked out of decision-making processEpilogue: Chicago and the nation},
