  abstract = {study of struggles for fair housing and integration maintenance; "Can we identify the factors that lead to success or failure in maintaining racial integration?" pxii; guided by three sociological fields -- race relations, social movements, and urban community pxiii "Integration is a process, not a number. We know this, and yet the numbers are what count in people's perceptions. And perceptison are at th eheart of this subject; they can and do make or break this movement." p24 " 'Tipping points' I do not include in this study, since there is no universal application of this concept." p25 to measure stability; use decades of numerical integration "as a synonym for pluralism meaning two or more diverse groups living peacably together in a cmoomon territory and sometimes joining in common effort." p25 field visits during 1984 "The visit to Hartford posted many problems in record collections, since the local oranization was not functioning any onger and earlier records had been mislaid or destroyed. Just when I thought I had located an important collection of organizational materials ina  former resident's basement, I found out tha the new owners had thrown them away as trash." p27 all names of local respondents changed Local level: Model A: Success Indianapolis (Butler-Tarkington Neighborhood Assoc) Rochester (19th Ward Community Assoc) Milwaukee (Sherman Park Community Association) Model B: Failure  [*this chapter was scanned and saved as PDF*] Hartford (Blue Hills Civic Association) author's acknowledgements: Bob and Martha Bellieveau, Bill Brayfield, Mary Collier, Jesse Collins, Ralph Dumas, Boyd Hinds (deceased), Linda Kelly, Howard Klebenoff, Jim Mason, Jim Miller, Dottie Payne, Gerri Porter, Bob Sadler, Rhea and Phil Starr, Geri Sullivan, Patricia Sweet, Allen Taylor, Margaret and Bill Worthington, CHS, HCourant, HPL, HPS author received phone number of BHCA from National Neighbors office, but at predom black meeting at St Justin's church in 1984, concluded that "This group was definitely not the BHCA, though it had the same initials and worked in the same neighborhood. the BHCA I knew about was surely dead, and Blue Hills was no longer an integrated comunity." p161 Hartford city historical background; see Pawlowski 1973;  on 1950s urban renewal that cleared 190 acres near downtown, dislocating more than 1200 households and 750 businesses; cites Hartford City Planning Dept 1983 report:  "By the end of that decade [1950s] Hartford lost more than 15,000 residents and numerous businesses...The combination of better highway systems, suburban housing opportunity and urban blight resulted in an exodus of moderate and upper income residents and the further concentration of urban poor" (p. 3 in original; p164 here) reviews HPS school deseg efforts (draws from Champ 1975)draws on words of former board member to interpret BHCA in three phases: (1) "to keep the blacks out" (1962-1965, 1965-1968); (2) "to achieve integration" (1969-1975); (3) "to have neighborhood stabilization -- meaning economic upkeep" (1976-1980), p188 sources for BCHA organizational history:  Blue Hills News paper, BHCA minutes, and Vincent Bolduc 1976 thesis a key dividing issue within the organization was the focus of its housing cmte (1965-69) attempted to counter panic selling by setting up own signs ("This Home NOT for Sale") also, formed real estate listing service in 1968 to counter block-busting realtors; distributed brochures to attract prospective buyers to Blue Hills, followed up with personal contacts and tours, p 194 real estate service transferred in 1969 from volunteers into a separate a separate entity -- Blue Hills Housing Services Corporation -- which faced internal dissent and dissolved in 1972 author's analysis: Blue Hills became 43\% black, up from 10\% a decade earlier; "the earliest statement about the new real estate service recognizes the difficulty of maintaining integration, and the fragility of stabilization, but it does not come to grips with the need for a specific strategy to achieve it. The statement refers to whites and blacks, but does not deal with racial groups as part of a planned strategy: 'Many...people have been discouraged from buying here by real estate agents who warned prospective white families that this area will be the nexxt ghetto. Many Negro families ahve contacted us to inquire whethr or not the area is in fact becomgin a ghetto and to inquire how the area would react to their living here' (News, May 1968)" p194-95 "The same inability to deal with a specific strategy for integration maintenance can be seen in a housing policy statement developed in November 1969"; BHCA Nov 1969 housing doc stresses "open occupancy" at first, then specific tactic for maintaining "the integrated quality of life in the neighborhood. This means that e will work to interest white families in living in the area...It is easy to misinterpret such a statement to say that it is opposed to open housing. In fact, the statement is an attempt to counteract the well-documented flight of white families out of the city, especially from area that are integrated. If we want to maintain an open neighborhood, it must be open to all in fact, not just in theory. Affirmative action is required to attrac and retain white families to the area generally, whiel at the same time we support open housing in every individual sale or rental." p195 author's analysis: document did not emphasize neighborhood quality issues or need for regional open housing for blacks; "Instead, the Blue Hills area continued to be the only hospitable neighborhood in the city for upwardly mobilie blacks, and their pent-up demand for housing resulted in continuing racial concentration inthe Blue Hills neighborhood." p196 controversy in BH Housing Services Corp over white-priority focus; see Bolduc 1976 thesis; HT 19 June 1971 editorial; sold 23 homes to whites form suburban areas; when "outspoken" BHCA members asked for "a clarificaiton of the corporation's racial policy" and questioned whether white preferences was racist, shareholders withdrew support and corporation dissolved p197 BHCA housing cmte continued monitoring and legal actions against real estate activities:  \#1) block-busting complaint filed with HUD on 11 Nov 1971, then ref to CT Comm on Human Rights and Opportunities, then filed in Federal district court; "When the agent gave up his real estate license, the court declared the case moot. It was the first use of fair housing law in the State of CT (letter from attorney to HUD, 5 June 1972)" \#2) racial-steering suit brought by Education/Instruccion (EI) "still another splinter group formed in 1971 by formerly active BHCA members and residents. EI was a general civil rights group that conducted educational research"p 197; housing test cases; lawsuit filed (with BHCA as one of several plaintiffs) in 1973-74 against 8 real estate firms; charges filed with US Dept of Justice 1974; investigated by FBI; denied by realtors (HC 21 Feb 1974); "A consent decree was issued in 1975, which required the companies to engage in fair housing practices and inform their staffs of provisioins of fair housing law. No admission of guilt was needed for the decree by Dept of Justice." p198 "Bob Harris, the former director of EI, a former BHCA member and Blue Hills resident and in 1984 one of the few remaining whites, said the Hartford newspapers woudl not print the story when first infomred of the findings, becuase 'they had so much money in real estate advertising' it would be bad for business. Finally, he said: 'We ended up going to Associated Press and it went out through the AP wires and came back in with theAP heading and was printed in both papers the same morning to protect them. That's how sad the situation had become'. He also complained that the State Human Rights Commission, formed to receive and act on discrimination complaints, was ineffective" p198 [backed up 18 months] BHCA housing cmte stopped functions 1972 "after several former BHCA leaders formed Urban Edge as a nonprofit fair housing real estate company p198 BHCA and Education "Even more vital and important than the early housing commitee was BHCA's education committee"; focus on school quality, but dwindled after 1973; "By this time the Blue Hills shcools were almost totally black" p198 "The BHCA's overrriding concern with education and the public schools was linked to the association's goal of preservation of a high-quality racially integrated neighborhood. Since the schools were such a vitally important neighborhood facility, association leaders belived it essential to have high-quality education in its neighborhood schools. the earliest reputation of BHCA was as a school-oriented organization -- "just a big PTA" -- as minutes of a 1969 board meeting reveal (Bolduc 1976: 137)" p199 author's analysis: "Prevention of impaction [85\% black in 1980] might have occurred in 1971 if the housing corporation had been encouraged to continue its policy of affirmative marketing... What might have succeeded in 1971 was a well-coordinated effort to recruit whites to the Blue Hills neighborhood at the same time that blacks were given expanded housing choices elsewhere. This could have been done in conjunction with the CT Housing investment Fund, which was heavily funded to assist blacks in moving to the suburbs. Unfortunately, CHIF also had internal problems and coflicts, andeventually turned its focus to rental counseling,k energy conservation, and the rehabilitation of existing units. Though its active couseling and mortgage assitance efforts helped over 1,900 minority families move to the suburbs throughout the state of CT, this died not help the Blue Hills area." p203 "But there was no ongoing fair housing problem of combating racial discrimiation in the housing market. The two legal suits filed in the early 1970s were a mere ripple in the tide of housing discrimination" p204 author cites four external forces that acted against BHCA neighborhood organization (p. 204): 1) urban renewal and land clearance in downtown Hartford that displaced thousands of minorities 2) racial discrimination in housing and mortgage markets that resulted in Northend racial concentration 3) public housing location --"Two massive public housing projects bordered the Blue Hills area, and their children were included in the Blue Hills neighborhood schools." 4) school racial imbalance -- "city efforts at desegregation occurring too late and too little to avert racial impaction of the Blue Hills schools" Why did BHCA decline? "One logical explanation for this might be that hte neighborhood became so overwhelmingly black, the original goal was then impossible to attain, and so there was no cause left to work for. but that is too simple. If we lok at other neighborhood stabilization organization we find that even when the neighborhood became predominantly black, the organization continued with a secondary goal of neighorhood maintenance and improvement -- a perfectly respectable second aim for a neighborhood group. Why didn't BHCA do this?  One difference between BHCA an the orther movement orgs studied is that this was the only organization that did not begin with the stated goal of integration maintenance. by the time new leaders and members openly acclaimed that goal in 1965, the neighborhood was already almost half-black, and the schools there were predominantly black." p209  [*author would be more direct if she stated that BHCA's original purpose was to prevent blacks from moving into neighborhood, as she quoted Bob Harris earlier*]  "Permost most important as a reason for burnout was the bitter internal conflict over affirmative marketing tactics, which further weakened the organization and caused the spin-offs of two other organizations." p210 Bob Harris criticizes Project Concern for drawing "highest quality black kids" away from neighborhood schools, p211 An older white couple, still iving in Blue Hills, on Weaver HS:  "I think that more recently people moved [away] because of the schools. The high school was once awfully good and it was predominantly white when it was built. After we moved here, white attendance just slid off the map... Very bad -- for white children" p212 also, HPS board did not adopt 1965 Harvard plan due to state funding concerns; HPS board "spent the next ten yeras implementing piecemeal segments of the plan, avoiding others, and circumventing still others" [cites Champ 1975, Brayfield 1975] p212 BHCA acronym taken over by Blue Hills Citizen Action, a group with paid organizers, not neighborhood volunteers now Blue Hills is stablizing low-middle-class black community, one of most influential political communities in the city, p213 author's final postscript notes that BHCA has been revived, and she is sending materials to new director [**remember that most names are pseudonyms*] Still looking for these sources: [not in WorldCat; trying to contact Saltman, currrent BHCA]: Thomas Champ, "Compromised Efforts at Desegregation." Hartford, mimeographed, 1975. Aviam Soifer "The Supreme Court's Desegregation Decisions: Unresolved Questions for the Hartford Desegregation Suit" U Conn School of Law, mimeographed, 1975 Model C: Conditional Akron (West Side Neighbors) profiles across the country National level:development of National Neighbors, the only national org devoted to the goal of integration maintenance},
